==English==
{{wikipedia}}
===Etymology===
From {{uder|en|grc|Ξενοφάνης|}}. The name means “of foreign appearance” and is composed of {{m|grc|ξένος||foreign}} + {{m|grc|φαίνω||appear}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/zɛˈnɒfəniːz/}}
===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun}}<!--plural Xenophaneses?-->
# A Greek [[given name]].
# The [[pre-Socratic]] philosopher [[w:Xenophanes|Xenophanes of Colophon]]; by extension or reference, any [[profound]] or [[transformative]] [[religious]] thinker.
#* {{quote-book|en|1931|Hermann Schneider & Margaret Minna Green|The History of World Civilization|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=8a9MkWjhZdkC|page=614|volume=2
|passage=Lucretius was the '''Xenophanes''' of Roman culture, a great theorist (visionary), an ardent disciple of Universal Nature, an enemy of all superstition, false gods, and false fear of death, {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1970|John Arthur Passmore|The Perfectibility of Man|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=KfTWAAAAMAAJ|page=77
|passage=No '''Xenophanes''' arose amongst the Jews to rebuke them for ascribing to Jahweh acts which would be accounted a shame and a disgrace amongst men; {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1985|Michael Despland|The Education of Desire|page=33|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=uwoEAQAAIAAJ
|passage=Euthyphro is no '''Xenophanes''' but as a religious and thinking man he can turn to great teachers; {{...}}}}
